author = "Johann D Bell and John L Munro and Warwick J Nash and Peter C Rothlisberg and Neil R Loneragan and Robert D Ward and Neil L Andrew",
abstract = "Publisher Summary This chapter presents the restocking initiatives for a wide variety of marine invertebrates such as, Giant Clams, Topshell, and Sea Cucumbers. The two immediate obstacles to restocking giant clams are the high cost of rearing clams until they are large enough to escape predation and the poaching of transplanted clams. The limited number of giant clams that can be produced for restocking highlights the need to maximize the reproductive contribution of each individual. The conclusion in the chapter that restocking of trochus (Topshell) is best accomplished by the translocation of adults provides an important focus for fisheries managers. A major reason that restocking is being assessed as a potential management tool for cultured sandfish is that increased numbers of sea cucumbers are unlikely to have detrimental effects on other important fauna. Development of technology for restocking sandfish has progressed to the point where the basic methods for propagating juveniles are available—but are now required to scale-up the production of juveniles cost-effectively—and for releasing cultured juveniles in the wild at high rates of survival. "
}
@incollection{Bell2005227,
title = "Management of Restocking and Stock Enhancement Programmes ",
