author = "Johann D Bell and John L Munro and Warwick J Nash and Peter C Rothlisberg and Neil R Loneragan and Robert D Ward and Neil L Andrew",
abstract = "Publisher Summary This chapter presents the lessons to provide guidance for the design, development, and implementation of future restocking or stock enhancement programs. The small differences in life-history traits among species, for example, larval duration; nursery habitats; vulnerability to predation; age at first maturity; feeding areas, which can have major effects on the approach required; and the costs involved for releasing marine invertebrates in restocking and stock enhancement programs. These differences have necessitated approaches as diverse as hatchery production of juveniles, collection of wild spat, provision of more settlement habitat, redistribution of settled juveniles, and translocation of adults. The broad range of case studies provides a clear message for fisheries agencies considering the use of restocking and stock enhancement as management tools, that is, there are no generic methods for such interventions. The variations in life history among species, the range of possible ways of increasing the numbers of juveniles, and the numerous failures, lead to the inescapable conclusion that there are no shortcuts to targeted research to identify whether a particular form of restocking or stock enhancement is likely to be cost-effective. "
}
@incollection{Bell2005277,
title = "Conclusions ",
